A binary file can run a process in foreground by simply
running the executable.

However, it will be unreliable, in the sense that if terminal
closes, the process will also close. Also , upon system reboot
the process won't come up automatically.

That's why we wrap the binary into a systemd service named like
xyz.service

The file xyz.service resides in /etc/systemd/system/xyz.service

This file xyz.service is called Unit File.

It can be something like this:

[Unit]
Description=xyz

[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/xyz
Restart=always
RestartSec=2

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

---
After it is created , it needs to be enabled via:

sudo systemctl enable xyz.service

Now, after a system reboot, the process will start 
automatically.
